<PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="NGA:-1997013 IGDB:18002987" id="Pl-1" latLong="9.083°N 7.533°E" state="FC" type="PPLC">ABUJA</PLACE>, July 1 (AFP)

<PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="NGA:-2020891 IGDB:17979109" id="Pl-2" latLong="10.000°N 8.000°E" type="COUNTRY">Nigerian</PLACE> police fired tear gas Tuesday to disperse protesters
gathering outside the government's main administrative offices on the
second day of a nationwide general strike.

A large contingent of riot police appeared determined to prevent a
protest building up outside the Federal Secretariat offices, as one
had on Monday when trade union activists barricaded the entrance with
parked cars.

As on Monday, police dispersed the demonstrators with a volley of
teargas, an AFP reporter saw.

Meanwhile, in the commercial capital <PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="NGA:-2017355 IGDB:17982645" id="Pl-5" latLong="6.453°N 3.396°E" state="LA" type="PPL">Lagos</PLACE> union officials said that
protesting students had begun building burning barricades around the
<PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="NGA:-2017355 IGDB:17982645" id="Pl-6" latLong="6.453°N 3.396°E" state="LA" type="PPL">Lagos</PLACE> State University Campus.

<PLACE country="NG" form="NAM" gazref="NGA:-2020891 IGDB:17979109" id="Pl-4" latLong="10.000°N 8.000°E" type="COUNTRY">Nigerian</PLACE> unions have launched a general strike in protest at a
government decision to hike the price of petrol and diesel by 54
percent.

